text: As much as I dig the cast, this looks like a play by play of every middle-of-the-road tropetastic fantasy-action flick ever made. Grizzled older dude action lead probably with not much personality other than brooding (probably got some dark back story or something), plucky other guy side character that gets some mildly funny one liners and to help the hero out, obligatory girl that is cute and half the lead's age but will definitely still be love interest for some reason (she's also probably a bit serious and will be mildly annoyed by the guys at some point / have a single scene where she shows them up by kicking more butt than they do). Ensuing fantasy-action with mild horror elements and mediocre cgi monsters. The evil is defeated. All go home. Yawwwwwn. God I'm so bored of the same old action movies. You can cast a bunch of oscar winners, it's not going to make the same tired premise, execution, characters, and tone any more interesting. Get some originality Hollywood. If not just by shaking up one or two elements at least.

text: Just went to see it. I thought it was decent but do have some thoughts on it. SPOILER WARNING :P I really think this movie should have just had a bad ending. Like, how the fuck does a mere human with a stupid sword win a 1 on 1 fight against the strongest witch of them all? He has no superpowers, she has superpowers! Him winning that is completely impossible, so he should have just lost, died, the witch queen wins, end of story. Or, if they desperately wanted at least a somewhat happy ending, the writers could have had Chloe form a resistance of good witches like herself to overthrow the evil queen or something, and then end it. OR, the witch queen, and witches in general, should have just been made much less powerful, for instance need more time to set up spells and shit, so a human could stand a chance against them. As it is, it's just so stupid that a weak ass human can kill an ultra powerful witch, with a SWORD of all weapons. Not only that, he actually took a couple of bullets before beating her too. Unbelievable. Kind of reminds me of Transcendence, that movie should have had a "bad" ending too. For almost the same reason, like in that movie you have this godlike sentient supercomputer, and that computer decides that it's best for the universe if it converts all humans to computers, right? So it begins setting it's plan in motion, and then this dumb human comes along, and tells this godlike machine that it's a bad plan to do all that?? And the machine is like "oh gosh you're right human, I guess I'm not so smart after all!" Or something? And then to top it all off, it even self destructs. So damn stupid. Good movies, though.

text: at 1:50 i couldn't contain my laughter any longer.  i'll rent this formidable turkey of epic proportions just to sate my perverse desire for bad movies. gawd, what a terrible flick this promises to be! truly, this should hold me over for months!  hilarious trailer... anything with 'the last' in the title is always awful... this wouldn't surprise me if there was 'a prophecy' thrown in just for shits and giggles....  despite how generic the trailer makes the movie seem, there could have been a good story here i bet. just drop vin diesel, he's just not this kind of action hero, but probably the only reason it barely made back its production budget. once you cast VD in this, though, you know exactly what to expect, eh? stick to cars, vin, it's what you're good at. quasi-horror, actiony bullshit, fighting demons with shotguns... yeah, not so much (unless you love that riddick bullshit, lol, then you're onboard probably).   it's just so easy to make these dumb things into something a little bit different, at least on the surface. here, we have the same-old-same-old nonsense we've seen a hundred times (which is no surprise considering the writers also shat out 'dracula untold,' too) ~ just a quarter turn would have made this seemingly unique.   oh, well, i'm sure this movie will be, uhm... text: Witchcraft in the 21rst century? Secret covens practicing the black arts to effect change for baneful work, hexes for revenge or for gain, intent on unleashing a black plague on the world.   The movie starts with a legion of witch hunters from the middle ages to battle evil spirits and their minions, Vin Diesel (Kaulder) is the master witch hunter. Kaulder discovers a witches lair with a large hideous tree of death, and tracks and destroys the queen of witches who places a hex on him, that he shall become immortal to carry on the fight.  One witch Chole (Rose Leslie of Game of Thrones) joins Kaulder and runs a Memory Bar, she can enter people‚Äôs dreams with visions to distract them. Kaulder is attended by faithful priests called the Dolans; Michael Caine and Elijah Wood. There‚Äôs also Belial (Olafur Darri Olafsson), an evil warlock and opponent who serves the Witch Queen.  Kaulder isn't just hunting and destroying witches throughout the last 800 hundred years, Kaulder has helped establish a truce and spends time as a Witch Judge, dealing fairly with practitioners of magic and only imprisoning the ones dabbling in the black arts.  Kaulder considers magic as neither a good or evil presence in the world, just something that exists and a force that must be dealt with. With Witchcraft you set your own limitations with your magical concept in which various fields of magical energy exist, your will or consciousness is the fundamental force to move your magic forward.  The magical forces of the world are controlled by nothing more than the will and concentration of the magician as you set your own limits, some for gain and benefit, others for malice or revenge.
